00:24:36.079 --> 00:24:40.880
Sorry, Rachel, I was trying to multitask here while you were asking that question, but yeah,

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:46.079
definitely. For those who don't know, I work at NASA, and we've been trying to implement a lot

00:24:46.079 --> 00:24:51.359
of different tools, and it's been a long, arduous journey over the last three or four years just

00:24:51.359 --> 00:24:57.199
trying to get an infrastructure set up, so it's definitely not an easy task within the government

00:24:57.199 --> 00:25:02.640
at times, and I'm sure the industry is the same way. But we've been able to do a lot of things

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:08.079
I'm sure the industry is the same way, but there's always a group that wants to use no-code,

00:25:08.079 --> 00:25:15.199
low-code type tools and just buy a vendor, which for some of the organizations in our agency that

00:25:15.199 --> 00:25:20.719
have the funding, maybe that's easy to do because they can spend that kind of money on a tool such

00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:27.119
as Alteryx, which costs us $5,000 a user per year, but my organization with little funds,

00:25:27.119 --> 00:25:33.680
we need to be able to do things with coding, so it's definitely just a matter of keeping

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:39.199
the conversation going and showing the value of open-source technologies and other resources

00:25:39.199 --> 00:25:43.680
rather than some of these no-code, low-code type tools, so it's not easy, but it can be done.

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:52.880
Thanks, David. Yeah, I see there's a lot of great conversation happening in the chat

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:56.079
around that as well, so if anybody else wants to weigh in, always

00:25:56.719 --> 00:25:58.880
feel free to raise your hand here on Zoom too.

