00:29:41.119 --> 00:29:46.479
Thank you very much. I see Sam, you asked a question in the chat, I think it has a star

00:29:46.479 --> 00:29:52.560
there, so I'll read it, but it's have you worked on projects where you inherited technical debt

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:56.800
and how have you tackled that to obtain a more future-proof solution?

00:29:59.280 --> 00:30:10.959
Yeah, sometimes there are projects that are just too good to pass on, but it is

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:18.800
like somebody started it, so you are inheriting it and then when you see the code, you are going

00:30:18.800 --> 00:30:30.560
to see a lot of to-do's in there and it's like, okay, good, it makes sense. Also, we have done

00:30:32.239 --> 00:30:37.920
work that needs to be done from scratch and given the circumstances, there are some unknowns,

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:47.760
so I understand that part, but yeah, I think the challenge sometimes is to know

00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:54.880
why they took some decisions on why they are doing this tool, why there are

00:30:56.160 --> 00:31:02.160
those to-do's. Sometimes, they don't make sense with the final infrastructure or the whole solution

00:31:03.119 --> 00:31:10.560
and yeah, I guess it's just tackle one by one, because there's always going to be that

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:19.839
technical debt. I think in one of the contracts that I remember that was very successful at that

00:31:19.839 --> 00:31:28.640
is that we had some overlap with the previous contractor, so they were able to tell us exactly

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:35.680
what that tech debt was there. These are the things that we didn't have time to do or that,

00:31:36.239 --> 00:31:43.040
because of priorities, we never got to this, and then we were able to have all those

00:31:43.680 --> 00:31:51.760
in tickets and then prioritize that. From what we heard, what they shared, this is what we need to

00:31:51.760 --> 00:32:01.680
work on right now before we jump into the actual work, and the rest is going to be just little by

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:08.800
little, and some of those tickets or things are not going to apply anymore sometimes, because

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:15.359
maybe we changed to another technology that we found was more cost-effective. Sometimes, we are

00:32:15.359 --> 00:32:22.160
inheriting projects that are maybe not super old, but yeah, maybe ten years, and ten years

00:32:23.359 --> 00:32:27.920
ago, the technology was very different, so yeah, this will be obviously more

00:32:29.359 --> 00:32:39.839
or better tools that we can just change, so yeah, some of the tech debt is not going to apply

00:32:39.839 --> 00:32:46.479
anymore, but I think if we have that opportunity to ask the previous contractor,

00:32:47.599 --> 00:32:55.199
we will have that and then prioritize. If not, then at the beginning, when we try to host that

00:32:55.199 --> 00:33:00.640
or to replicate the infrastructure is when we are going to see the biggest things that we need to

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:08.319
tackle, and the hidden ones are those to-dos in the code, because you don't see it right away,

00:33:08.319 --> 00:33:14.079
but one thing that you could do is just try to find them. Just look at all the to-dos in the code

00:33:14.079 --> 00:33:22.959
and see if you can identify one of those that are really big or important. You're not going to,

00:33:22.959 --> 00:33:28.640
in some cases, maybe most of them, or you're not going to be able to tackle all of them.

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:35.359
Sometimes, this is really huge, but yeah, I guess just prioritize and focus on the big ones.

00:33:38.880 --> 00:33:46.160
Thank you. I'd love to hear a little bit more about your journey as well, and you're

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:51.680
jumping from generalist software engineer to specialized data engineer and what that was like.

00:33:53.359 --> 00:34:02.319
Yeah, so I graduated as a computer systems engineer, and at the beginning, I didn't know

00:34:03.119 --> 00:34:10.159
what to do. I didn't know what the industry was offering to begin with, so I was just saying

00:34:10.159 --> 00:34:19.040
yes to any offer, like whatever life was throwing at me, and so I had the opportunity to have very

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:26.879
different jobs, so at the beginning, I was a front-end developer, so I was migrating an

00:34:26.879 --> 00:34:33.199
application. I will sound very old, but yeah, that was a standalone application in a mainframe, so

00:34:33.199 --> 00:34:40.719
with green screens and that, I was migrating that to the web, and so I learned some web development

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:50.320
that later on didn't help me a lot, because I was using technology that is not used anymore,

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:58.639
but I was using Java, and Java really helped me out later. From that, I jumped to be a tester, so I

00:34:58.639 --> 00:35:07.360
was doing software validation for aircraft engines, so a whole new thing, and then I jumped into the

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:15.120
retail sector doing back-end for an operating system, so there, I was using Java as well,

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:24.239
and some C or C++, so it was more like low-level programming, and that helped me a lot with my

00:35:24.239 --> 00:35:31.679
programming skills, because that's where, since it was a very low level, and it was like programming

00:35:31.679 --> 00:35:37.840
like the signals that the keyboard sends to the operating system, things like that, you need to

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:44.239
use a lot of like linked lists, arrays, vectors, so all those data structures that I was like, I'm not

00:35:44.239 --> 00:35:52.800
going to use this when I work. Well, I was using all of those, but that helped me with my coding

00:35:52.800 --> 00:36:03.760
skills. Then, all of that was in Mexico, and I also was a data engineer in Mexico. That was my

00:36:03.760 --> 00:36:14.159
last job, and then I moved to the United States, and I, at that point, I knew I wanted to work with

00:36:14.159 --> 00:36:20.800
data, because I really liked that. It wasn't like as low-level as operating system, and

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:30.399
but still, I got to use those coding skills to be parsing data, so I really liked that,

00:36:30.959 --> 00:36:41.040
but when I was here, I knew that I needed to get any opportunity that I have, and I was,

00:36:41.919 --> 00:36:51.120
I learned some web application, web development frameworks like Ruby on Rails, PHP on Django,

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:59.120
and PHP with Drupal, and Go, like different stacks there, and so I felt that I was like moving around.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:04.879
I also was in the infrastructure team for a while, so I was learning a lot, and that

00:37:05.919 --> 00:37:17.280
was helping me to get or to be put into contracts, because I was able to do a lot of

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:25.280
stuff. Maybe I wasn't very knowledgeable in anything, but I knew a lot. I mean, it was very

00:37:25.280 --> 00:37:36.159
wide, not deep, but I really wanted to go, so one, go back to data, and two, start specializing

00:37:36.159 --> 00:37:44.639
in something. I felt like, okay, I enjoyed all that, like learning all those skills,

00:37:44.639 --> 00:37:52.639
but I was seeing other people that they really know a lot of what they know, so I wanted to be

00:37:52.639 --> 00:37:59.360
like that, so whenever I was able to be in data contracts, because I wanted to

00:38:00.159 --> 00:38:05.600
to keep working for the federal government, so to do that, you need some clearances, especially

00:38:05.600 --> 00:38:11.280
when you are seeing data, and to do that, I needed to be a US resident, so finally, I became one,

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:18.080
and I was able to move to the data field again, and that's when I started specializing more,

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:27.439
and yeah, I really like that, because there's just too much to learn in all these

00:38:27.439 --> 00:38:35.679
fields, like infrastructure, front-end, back-end, and it can get crazy sometimes, and just in data,

00:38:35.679 --> 00:38:42.399
there's a lot to learn as well, but at least I'm more focused now on what I want to do or where

00:38:42.879 --> 00:38:51.040
I want to go. That's great. Thank you, and I agree with Libby. Love to hear the generalist

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:57.280
versus specialist conversation. I see Victor, you had asked a question in the chat. Do you want to

00:38:57.280 --> 00:39:08.719
jump in? And I can read the question to it. It was, what should be the roadmap to data science

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:15.040
based on your experience? And Victor, I'm curious of what perspective that's coming from,

00:39:15.040 --> 00:39:19.280
like just starting to learn data science or which role you're in now?

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:33.199
I think it's mute. Yeah, I think it's, yeah, I don't know if I really can answer that,

00:39:33.439 --> 00:39:42.159
but I will tell any person that wants to go to data science is, well, first find a mentor

00:39:42.159 --> 00:39:51.760
that can really help you or guide you in that part, but as a data engineer, I will encourage

00:39:51.840 --> 00:40:00.080
you to use cloud tools to learn that part. I know that data engineering may not be

00:40:02.879 --> 00:40:09.439
the career path that you want to go, but you will always need some data engineering skills,

00:40:10.159 --> 00:40:18.719
especially if you want to show something or to prototype something, and you can be able to do

00:40:18.719 --> 00:40:27.840
that yourself. Just small projects, you don't have to start with big data, but obviously,

00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:33.760
if the scope of the project is huge, you will need a lot of teams. You need data engineers,

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:40.399
infrastructure engineers, but just to know what all the teams do, I think that's going to be very

00:40:40.479 --> 00:40:49.439
helpful when you want to collaborate with others, so it will help you to collaborate and also

00:40:50.479 --> 00:40:59.679
to do your research or analysis yourself easier, because you won't depend on anyone, so you can

00:40:59.679 --> 00:41:07.760
start using some tools, like, for example, if you want to use AWS, you can start using S3 for

00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:14.320
storage and maybe start playing around with Athena or with Glue for transforming the data,

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:25.040
and then when you want that, so you want to show a proof of concept, maybe someone can take that

00:41:26.159 --> 00:41:34.560
and scale that, and yeah, I think as a data scientist, you still need to clean your data

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:43.040
anyway, so I think that's a part that I can't talk about. I know that there are other skills, like

00:41:45.439 --> 00:41:54.800
statistics or data analysis, but that's not my area of expertise. I just really encourage you

00:41:55.840 --> 00:42:02.479
to grow also in your data engineering skills. That will make you a more solid data scientist,

00:42:02.479 --> 00:42:10.560
maybe at the beginning, you need to focus on other skills, but if you want to jump into the

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:19.120
industry, you will always need to do something in a small scale. That's really helpful. Thank you.

00:42:20.399 --> 00:42:26.000
I know, Mandeep, you had asked a question a little bit earlier in the chat. Do you want to jump in

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:34.560
and ask that? Yeah, for sure. Hi, everybody. My question is around the languages. You talked

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:41.120
a lot about a variety of languages that you've worked with, and languages are similar and

00:42:41.120 --> 00:42:46.479
dissimilar in different ways. Do you have a framework when jumping between the different

00:42:46.479 --> 00:42:52.479
languages, and if so, what is the first thing that you look at when you're looking at a new

00:42:52.479 --> 00:42:57.040
language that you're going to use, or a new framework within AWS, for example? What are

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:08.399
you looking for? Yeah, that's a really good question. When I need to learn a new language,

00:43:08.959 --> 00:43:18.639
the first thing that I want to see is the data types. They can change slightly between languages,

00:43:18.639 --> 00:43:24.879
but that's the first thing that you need to work with, with variables. So, if you have a text,

00:43:24.879 --> 00:43:30.639
it's going to be a string or it's going to be another name. If you have a boolean, it's going

00:43:30.639 --> 00:43:44.080
to be just bool or boolean, just to know the data types, and then the flow, the syntax to do those

00:43:44.080 --> 00:43:58.159
flows, like the if, for, while, or switch case, or other. I forgot the name of what those are

00:43:58.159 --> 00:44:06.959
called, but yeah, how to do those flows, because yeah, as well, they change between languages,

00:44:06.959 --> 00:44:14.879
and they have slide changes sometimes. It's for, and then the name of your temporary variable,

00:44:14.879 --> 00:44:20.639
and then colon, and the list, and sometimes it's between parentheses, and you need to do it

00:44:20.639 --> 00:44:26.399
all the way around. Just knowing that can let you start with that. So, at the beginning,

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:38.239
my code is super basic. It will have a lot of if and fors, and maybe that's all, but little by

00:44:38.239 --> 00:44:45.199
little, I started learning more of the ways of optimizing the code, but I think that's the very,

00:44:45.199 --> 00:44:53.919
very first thing that I do or try to learn, and one of the things that you also need to do,

00:44:54.000 --> 00:45:01.600
especially in data, is just open a file, open a CSV, open an Excel file, open a JSON file. So,

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:10.000
that's something that I will do next. So, how am I going to read a JSON file? So, I try to learn

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:17.120
that. So, what is the code that I will use? If it is Python, for example, you will do it with Pandas.

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:25.600
They're just like a very easy function to do that, and that brings me to another thing.

00:45:27.120 --> 00:45:33.120
Sometimes the language is not specialized to handle data. For example, Python with R,

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:40.959
like that's specifically for doing statistics and data, so it's very easy to use for that,

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:50.639
but Python wasn't created for data. So, that's another thing that you will need to do, like what

00:45:50.639 --> 00:45:56.000
are the libraries that are used for data analysis? So, okay, it is Python, and then you will say,

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:02.719
okay, there's NumPy, there's Pandas, and then try to see the documentation and what are the

00:46:02.719 --> 00:46:09.360
things that you can do with the data. So, that will be maybe the last thing I will do, and then

00:46:09.360 --> 00:46:14.800
it's just practice, just practice and trying to get better at it.

00:46:18.479 --> 00:46:23.280
Thank you. I see there are a few Slido questions that touch upon a similar

00:46:24.879 --> 00:46:29.760
idea, and one was asking about what your tech stack looks like,

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:35.040
and then the other is around preferences for data visualization and why.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:43.679
Sure. So, for tech stack, it depends on the contract I am working on. So, yeah, I don't have

00:46:43.679 --> 00:46:56.800
like one specific one. In Vixel, we try to push to use AWS, and we have this, the infrastructure,

00:46:57.600 --> 00:47:02.959
we did like an environment that we can reproduce, so we are using Terraform,

00:47:03.919 --> 00:47:10.399
so that's why we like that. So, if we know that we are going to need some extra buckets, maybe

00:47:11.439 --> 00:47:20.159
a way to transform the data with AWS Glue or Lambda and then another storage, we can deploy

00:47:20.159 --> 00:47:26.560
that infrastructure very quickly because we have that already in Terraform. So, that's what we try

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:35.679
to use, and also it has all the requirements that some federal contracts require that are

00:47:37.199 --> 00:47:46.959
like the security compliances like FedRAMP, for example. So, if we are free to use any tech stack,

00:47:46.959 --> 00:47:55.760
we are going to use AWS for sure, and for doing the ETL or the extract and form load process,

00:47:56.560 --> 00:48:06.719
we tend to use Python just because it's easier to deploy that to AWS, and it's always easier

00:48:07.360 --> 00:48:15.600
to find people that know Python. At some point, we were leaning more into R, but it was hard to

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:21.840
find people. It was harder to, especially like two years ago, it was harder to use it in the cloud.

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:33.280
Right now, it is getting better. For the data visualization tools, well, I like Shiny. I've

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:41.919
worked with Shiny on RStudio, and it's just very fun. It's very fun to work with and trying to

00:48:41.919 --> 00:48:49.199
make your charts and visualizations prettier and interactive. I really enjoyed working with that

00:48:49.199 --> 00:48:56.479
one, so I recommend that one just because it's fun, because I really like it, and you can customize

00:48:56.479 --> 00:49:04.000
it as much as you need. Sometimes, when you're using a tool like Power BI or Tableau and then

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:08.320
the customer is like, oh, I want to have my branding and my theming, sometimes it's not as

00:49:08.320 --> 00:49:18.879
easy to customize it as much as the client wants, but it also depends on the time or the resources

00:49:18.879 --> 00:49:24.959
that you have. If you have limited time, sometimes Tableau is the easiest

00:49:26.159 --> 00:49:33.280
way to go, and also it's the one that the client knows the most, so if we can do it our way,

00:49:34.159 --> 00:49:40.959
maybe we're going to go, and we have unlimited time, we will need to decide between doing it

00:49:40.959 --> 00:49:46.159
with Shiny or maybe a React application. It also depends on who is going to do it,

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:53.120
but my favorite one, it will be Shiny and Tableau.

