you could do when you are in the prototyping phase, especially if it is private data that

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:24.639
you cannot share, that you shouldn't share that, like never in GitHub, but

00:51:25.439 --> 00:51:35.840
we have used two options there, so just upload the data into S3 and give access to the people

00:51:35.840 --> 00:51:46.000
that need to have access, and with S3, that's a good tool because it is reliable and it's scalable,

00:51:46.399 --> 00:51:51.679
and it's scalable, so you can just upload as much data as you want,

00:51:53.040 --> 00:52:01.919
and you can also restrict the data depending on what people can see, so you can assign roles

00:52:01.919 --> 00:52:06.879
to the people and they will only see what they need to see, so that's a good solution,

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:15.919
and another one that we have used, and this is if people that are not very technical are

00:52:15.919 --> 00:52:20.560
going to be participating, we use SharePoint because we use a lot of Microsoft tools,

00:52:20.560 --> 00:52:26.479
so we have Teams and Outlook, so a lot of people are already familiar, I mean,

00:52:26.479 --> 00:52:30.239
within Bixel, they're already familiar with SharePoint, so that's a tool that we are going

00:52:30.239 --> 00:52:39.679
to use, and you can also restrict the data. I think we will prefer S3, but depending on the

00:52:39.679 --> 00:52:46.239
people that we are going to be collaborating with, maybe we are going to be using SharePoint,

00:52:46.239 --> 00:52:52.479
and then when you are setting up your environment, we know where to go to download the data,

00:52:52.479 --> 00:52:59.280
and if it is S3, you can just call it from your code. If you have access,

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:05.520
you just need your AWS keys and you can just programmatically download that data. If it is

00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:13.520
SharePoint, I think there's a way to do it. We haven't used those, but that's something to explore,

00:53:14.479 --> 00:53:24.479
and also, we use a lot of web applications. We use Drupal, which is a PHP framework for

00:53:24.479 --> 00:53:31.439
content management, and if we need to download data from there or to use content that is in there,

00:53:32.399 --> 00:53:38.800
if the web application is within the company, so Bixel developers are maintaining it,

00:53:38.800 --> 00:53:46.159
we can ask them to create an API for us, so Drupal has the ability to enable the API,

00:53:46.159 --> 00:53:52.239
and then we can use it, or we can request them exactly what data we need, and they will

00:53:53.040 --> 00:53:59.600
implement that endpoint for us, and then we just use it. So, I think those are the three

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:04.320
options that we use when we need to share information internally.

00:54:06.719 --> 00:54:09.199
I hope that answers your question. Thank you. Oh, yeah, that was great. Thank you.

00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:14.800
And Jorge, I see you asked a question in the Zoom chat

00:54:15.919 --> 00:54:20.000
around data engineering positions. Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:54:22.800 --> 00:54:33.120
Yeah, sure. Yeah, yeah, that's fine. Sorry. So, the question is regarding just when I was

00:54:33.120 --> 00:54:40.320
transitioning from developer to working in machine learning, I came across a lot of positions that

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:46.320
were in data engineering, and oftentimes, when I had the conversation with the – sorry, I think

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:53.919
my camera's locked. Oftentimes, when I had a conversation with a recruiter, as soon as they

00:54:53.919 --> 00:54:59.439
heard that I didn't have experience in, like, Spark or any of the other distributed computing

00:54:59.439 --> 00:55:07.199
systems, MapReduce, all of those, I only covered it in grad school. I didn't use it in, like,

00:55:07.199 --> 00:55:13.120
any job, so they just immediately lost interest, and they said, no, we just need interest – you

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:19.439
know, we need people with experience in those, and that was it, right? So, do you find experience

00:55:19.439 --> 00:55:29.399
in those frameworks necessary to be a data engineer? So, you will learn that, but to –

00:55:29.439 --> 00:55:38.399
when I am hiring people for a data engineer position, I focus more on the programming skills.

00:55:38.479 --> 00:55:47.600
If you are a good engineer, you will learn Spark or MapReduce in no time. Like, seriously, it's not –

00:55:47.600 --> 00:55:57.919
I wouldn't want to lose a good engineer because of one skill. Yeah, no, I don't think – I mean,

00:55:58.639 --> 00:56:08.159
it is necessary in terms of you will end up using them, but in my opinion, I wouldn't

00:56:08.159 --> 00:56:14.239
say no to a person that I know is good, and I can teach them or mentor them in these

00:56:15.120 --> 00:56:23.439
frameworks. When I started, like, my first job as a data engineer, I didn't know any of those. I

00:56:23.439 --> 00:56:30.719
didn't know what big data was or MapReduce or Spark. I had a lot of experience with Java.

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:38.239
That's why they hired me, because they were like, okay, she knows Java. She knows how to program.

00:56:38.239 --> 00:56:45.439
That's more important, and I think I agree with that, and that's the philosophy that I still

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:57.840
follow up to this moment, and so, yeah, programming skills, that's basic. You really need to know how

00:56:57.840 --> 00:57:07.760
to use code, and if it is one programming language that it is more common in data, like

00:57:07.760 --> 00:57:15.199
Java or Scala, Python or R, it's going to be better. If your programming language is more

00:57:15.199 --> 00:57:22.159
like PHP or Ruby, those are good. I would really encourage you to learn Python, though,

00:57:22.639 --> 00:57:36.560
but yeah, I don't feel those, like Spark or MapReduce, are really important or necessary

00:57:36.560 --> 00:57:42.320
when you are looking for a job, although if you are having that experience,

00:57:45.040 --> 00:57:49.919
maybe you can do a personal project and try to use, for example, if you know,

00:57:50.879 --> 00:57:55.840
do you know Python? Yeah, no, I mean, I'm not in that position anymore,

00:57:55.840 --> 00:58:01.199
right, but it was when I was transitioning. I often found it, and I wasn't specifically looking

00:58:01.199 --> 00:58:08.639
for data engineering jobs. I was looking for machine learning engineer jobs, and sometimes

00:58:08.639 --> 00:58:12.639
recruiters contacted me for data engineering jobs, and I thought that maybe that was a good

00:58:12.639 --> 00:58:20.000
transition, right, like if I wanted to transfer, to transition, and it never, like it never panned

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:25.919
out because of that, because of that lack of experience, and so I just moved, so I jumped,

00:58:25.919 --> 00:58:30.399
I was able to jump positions and went straight to working in machine learning.

00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:37.840
So, it turns out better than, yeah, no, no, that's it, but yeah, but the idea is actually good,

00:58:37.840 --> 00:58:42.320
like being a data engineer and then jump to machine learning. I think that makes sense.

00:58:43.040 --> 00:58:51.040
But yeah, if anyone is in, like, in that position, first, I will try to show up my programming

00:58:51.040 --> 00:58:57.520
skills, and if you have the time, like maybe do a personal project where you can use, for example,

00:58:57.520 --> 00:59:04.320
if you know Python, then use PySpark, just play around with it so you can show that you know how

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:11.120
to use it, you know, I think what they are looking for that you have experience with concurrency

00:59:11.120 --> 00:59:18.399
or parallel jobs, like what you are saying here, like distributed computer frameworks,

00:59:18.959 --> 00:59:24.399
sometimes you need to think a bit differently, but if you start, like, playing around and

00:59:24.399 --> 00:59:29.760
reading about that, like that will give you a better opportunity to learn that job.

00:59:32.239 --> 00:59:37.120
I love Brittany's comment in the chat. Brittany didn't mean to put you on the spot,

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:38.320
but if you want to share that.

00:59:41.040 --> 00:59:47.040
Sure, yeah. So, sometimes what I've found being both on the candidate side and on

00:59:47.840 --> 00:59:52.239
the interviewer side is that, especially when you are working through a third party, like

00:59:52.239 --> 00:59:59.840
a hiring recruiter, they may not know all of the things, like they are given the job description,

00:59:59.840 --> 01:00:04.800
and they may not know that, hey, I really need someone who has this skill, but if they don't

01:00:04.800 --> 01:00:09.840
have this particular one, I'm willing to train on that, and sometimes the recruiter doesn't know

01:00:09.840 --> 01:00:15.439
that information, and it might honestly change depending on how long the role is open for,

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:20.800
and so, like, I think what's best for the candidate in that case is to try to get

01:00:21.520 --> 01:00:27.120
as close to whomever the actual hiring manager is as possible, and then just let them, like,

01:00:27.120 --> 01:00:31.199
give them your resume and let them know your experience, because sometimes they'll look at

01:00:31.199 --> 01:00:35.199
your resume and they would absolutely love to give you an interview where the recruiter might say,

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:40.080
oh, you don't meet X percent of the job description, therefore I'm not going to pass it on,

01:00:40.879 --> 01:00:46.560
so it's just, it's one of those disconnects between having a third party sort of do that interfacing.

01:00:48.719 --> 01:00:56.399
Yeah, I totally agree with that. We don't always do a good job specifying what, like, the key

01:00:57.120 --> 01:01:00.800
skills that we want in a candidate, and yeah, some recruiters will just

01:01:02.800 --> 01:01:04.879
say no or reject people that are really good.

